comments.message:
It's usually frowned upon to do bare pointer management.  I would say to use a std::unique_ptr<OccCommand> instead, but since the lifetime matches the Status objects lifetime  it seems like you could just have this be a normal OccCommand.

Does _pt  refer to pass through? I think this app already uses passthrough to refer to when an external user sends in a command that this daemon passes through to the OCC.  Maybe  just occCmd?

Sorry, one more comment.  Having public member variables is also frowned upon.  You could just make it private and then have:

OccCommand& getCommand()
{
   return occCmd;
}

nit: I like this way:
```
if (activeCount < 1)
{
  log<level::INFO>("Manager::pollerTimerExpire(): No OCCs running, poll "
                         "timer not restarted");
  return;
}

if (!_pollTimer)
{
  log<level::ERR>(
                "Manager::pollerTimerExpired() ERROR: Timer not defined");
  return;
}

for (auto& obj : statusObjects)
{
   // Read sysfs to force kernel to poll OCC
   obj->readOccState();
}

// Restart OCC poll timer
_pollTimer->restartOnce(std::chrono::seconds(pollInterval));
```
